<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker A · exact canon excerpt</p>
  <h2>Article Eight</h2>
  <blockquote class="reading"><p>The whole of the law is that what action harms¹ none is a right; that what is done to preserve life according to and in balance with nature² is a right; that what is done to resist coercion³, or aid another to do the same, is a right; that what is done in the presence of informed⁴ consent⁵ is a right.</p><p>Let it be known: to steal the tools an individual uses to obtain a living or practice their art is tantamount to murder.</p></blockquote>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="panel"><h3>Plain orientation</h3><p>Article Eight defines rights by relation to harm, life, nature, coercion, consent, and tools of survival. It is less a list of permissions than a test for whether action preserves agency and life.</p></article>
    <article class="panel"><h3>Central tension</h3><p>The article protects liberty, but every term is difficult: harm, nature, coercion, informed, consent. Article Seven’s definition work is required before Article Eight can be applied safely.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>
<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker B · footnote conversation</p>
  <h2>What the notes keep from collapsing</h2>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ¹ · harm</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> Without debate, freedom is dead.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> prevents harm from being declared by authority alone. The right to debate keeps freedom from being replaced by accusation.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ² · nature</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> a complex system requiring consumption of the dead for continued participation.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> rejects sanitized nature. Life persists through cycles, dependency, death, and transformation.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ³ · coercion</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> save for parents or appointed guardians of children or invalids.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> names a hard exception: care for those who cannot safely exercise full independent agency may include constraint, but that exception is dangerous and must remain bounded.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁴ · informed</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> a Myth as reality defies certainty.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> keeps informed consent humble. No one knows everything; the duty is meaningful disclosure, not impossible omniscience.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁵ · consent</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> sexuality, as practiced by Political Adults, respects no limitations beyond consent - love as thou wilt provided children receive care.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> makes consent the governing boundary for adult intimacy while retaining child care as a non-negotiable obligation.</p></article>
</section>
