<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Rights with living limits</h2>
  <p>Article Eight gives a rights test. A right is not merely what someone wants. A right is action that does not harm, preserves life in balance with nature, resists coercion, aids resistance to coercion, or occurs with informed consent.</p>
  <p>Applying this article requires definitions. Harm must be debated. Nature must be understood as a living system. Coercion must be identified without making care impossible. Consent must be meaningful despite incomplete knowledge.</p>
  <p>The final sentence about tools is practical: to take the means by which a person survives or practices art is to attack their life-process.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> What makes a right?</p>
  <p>Article Eight asks a hard question: what makes an action a right?</p>
  <p>The answer is not simply desire. An action is a right when it harms none, preserves life in balance with nature, resists coercion, aids another resisting coercion, or happens in the presence of informed consent.</p>
  <p>Every one of those words needs care. Harm must be debated. Nature is not clean and sentimental; it is a complex system. Coercion has exceptions for guardianship, but exceptions must be watched. Informed consent is never perfect, because reality defeats certainty.</p>
  <p>Then the article lands on something concrete: stealing the tools someone uses to live or practice their art is tantamount to murder. Because survival is not abstract. Agency needs tools.</p>
</section>
